    - term: 'Frequency '
      unit: f
      type: 1
      description: Number of events per unit of time
      details: 'The number of events per unit of time. For periodic motion, frequency
        is the number of oscillations per unit time. The relationship between frequency
        and period is


        Frequency: f = 1/T

        Hooke''s Law: F_r = -kx'
    - term: Hooke's Law
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: Objects attached to a spring or any elastic object with negligible
        mass
      details: "These objects are generally called pendulums, whereas the objects
        that undergo Hooke\u2019s Law are called springs. Take, for example, a simple
        pendulum that moves back and forth at a certain angle, 0. In its motion lie
        two equal angles, which can be shown by bisecting the angle itself. What
        lies between are two angles, 00 and \u221200. These two angles can be demonstrated
        below."
    - term: Springs
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: Objects that undergo Hooke's Law
      details: "A simple pendulum that moves back and forth at a certain angle, 0.
        In its motion lie two equal angles, which can be shown by bisecting the angle
        itself. What lies between are two angles, 00 and \u221200. These two angles
        can be demonstrated below.\r\n"
  - level: 32
    terms:
    - term: Harmonic Motion
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: Kind of motion that show repetition and definite pattern
      details: Its root word harmony, defines a kind of motion that shows repetition
        and definite pattern. This pattern is a wave, which is the driving mechanism
        of our songs, our sounds, and any other sounds we create and associate with.
        With this fascination with sound comes acoustics.
    - term: Acoustics
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: Branch of science dealing with study, analysis, and application
        of sound
      details: The branch of science dealing with the study, analysis, and application
        of sound, which is a disturbance of molecules within a given substance. This
        disturbance must be caused by a wave, however. In this context, a wave is
        not just a graphical representation of harmonic motion; rather, it is a medium
        that drives a substance to disturb its molecules by use of harmonic motion.
        This harmonic motion is called vibration.
    - term: Wave
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: iI not only propagate sounds but also electrical signals, lights,
        and so on
      details: A medium where sound propagates without carrying over the matter where
        it moves. Waves do not only carry sounds, however. Different waves propagate
        different things, such as electrical signals, light, and so on. Such a wave
        is a mechanical wave.
    - term: Mechanical Wave
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: Wave that results from interaction with matter, has limited transmission
        of matter
      details: "a wave that results from interaction with matter. An example would
        be a child driving a rope tied to a post to form waves. In this example,
        the child is delivering force onto the rope, which creates a wave carrying
        the force. This force has a certain amount of energy traveling from the boy\u2019s
        hand up to the tree. Thus, the wave dies if it hits the tree, and if the
        child has had enough of creating waves. This wave has a limited transmission
        of matter."
    - term: Surface Wave
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: A wave that propagates along with the interface between different
        media.
      details: "This mechanical wave creates a disturbance on the matter\u2019s surface,
        hence the name. The wave generated carries over the energy of the source
        of the disturbance. As an example, if pressure builds up underneath the surface
        of the Earth, the resulting pent-up pressure generates surface waves along
        the planet\u2019s surface, carrying over the energy stored."
    - term: Longitudinal Wave
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: 'A wave whose vibrations travel along the direction of the wave. '
      details: A wave whose vibrations travel along the direction of the wave. Thus,
        if a wave is moving to the right, the vibrations also move to the right.
        This wave creates areas of compression where loose molecules clump together
        during transmission at certain intervals. This wave travels fastest in a
        solid, which becomes nonexistent in a vacuum, where no molecules can support
        the wave. An example of this wave is sound.
    - term: Transverse Wave
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: "A wave whose vibrations travel perpendicularly from the wave\u2019s
        direction."
      details: "A wave whose vibrations travel perpendicularly from the wave\u2019s
        direction. It travels at certain intervals and is usually drawn like a sine
        curve. It travels the fastest in a vacuum, which becomes nonexistent in a
        solid, where the matter only absorbs the energy carried by the wave. An example
        of this wave is light, which is made up of two (2) perpendicular waves coexisting
        as one beam of light."
    - term: 'Wave Speed '
      unit: v
      type: 2
      description: Measure how fast a wave propagates from so
      details: "Wave speed (V) is the measure of how fast a wave propagates from
        the source traveling outwards. It follows the same tenet as linear motion\u2019s
        velocity, where\n\nWave Speed: v = d\u03BB/dT"
